ful details and new characters which, of course, I could invent, but I have come to the conclusion that artistically it would be all wrong because it would tend to bulge out and upset the unity and symmetry of the whole play as it is planned now.

I am now going to tackle the Third Act.

I am attaching a page from the Spring issue of The Partisan Review which you may have already seen.1





Sincerely yours,

Vladimir Nabokov





